english:
  title: Stele Inscription for the Divine and Virtuous Queen, Mother of the Founding King of Joseon
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since ancient times, when emperors receive the Mandate of Heaven and rise to power, they have relied upon the virtue of their consorts to share in their achievements and nurture blessings that extend their dynasty's lineage forever. The Great Yu of the Xia had the Lady of Tushan, through whom his son Qi could continue his legacy; the Zhou had the Grand Matriarch, through whom King Wu could undertake great enterprises. Thus the sacred rites of these luminaries were sustained in perpetuity.

    How glorious indeed! Our Divine and Virtuous Queen possessed an inherent purity and dignity, with the gentle virtue and chaste constancy befitting a consort. Early she joined our High Lord in his humble station, aided him in establishing kingship, and bore wise and worthy sons whose line shall endure without limit. Her sacred accomplishments and exemplary conduct rival those of the sage consorts of antiquity. Yet one sorrow remains: the great enterprise neared its fulfillment when she too hastily departed this world. The High Lord founded the nation yet could not honor her as queen; two wise sons inherited the throne yet could not provide her the glory of support in her final years. The royal tomb now obscures her radiance, and frost and dew only deepen our grief.

    Originally titled the Virtuous Consort, her tomb was named Altar of Harmony. Later she received the posthumous name Divine and Virtuous Queen. The Benevolent Brilliance Hall was established to preserve her image, and the rites of elevation have been duly observed. Our sovereign lord, grieved that the beloved visage of his mother remains forever hidden and unable to fulfill his filial devotion, has commanded the competent officials to carve a great stele. He has ordered this humble minister to compose an inscription, that it may illuminate future generations.

    This minister, receiving such command, trembles in fear and dares not refuse. I have humbly investigated the matter: The Queen bore the surname Han, descended from the honored house of Anbyeon. Her father, whose name was Kyeong, was posthumously honored with the title of Meritorious Retainer for Faithful Service and Virtuous Cultivation, bearing the rank of Grand Commandant of Three Hans and Three Ranks, having served as Director of the Chancellery and Lord of Ancheon.

    Her grandfather, whose name was Kyul-in, received the posthumous honor of Meritorious Retainer for Benevolent Cultivation and Harmonious Transformation, holding the rank of Senior Minister of the Left and Judge of the Bureau of Civil Appointments, also made Lord of Ancheon.

    Her great-grandfather, whose name was Yu, received posthumous honor as Meritorious Retainer for Pure Sincerity and Virtuous Cultivation, holding rank as Senior Minister of the Right and Concurrent Judge of the Bureau of Revenue, made Lord of Anwon.

    Her mother was of the Shin clan, honored as Grand Lady of Three Hans, daughter of Won-ryeo who held high office.

    From childhood the Queen displayed refined grace and extraordinary wisdom. When of marriageable age, she was chosen to be the consort of our High Lord. During those decades when he served as general and prime minister, engaging constantly in warfare with no year of peace, the Queen devoted herself wholly to managing the household and encouraging his endeavors. By nature free from jealousy, she treated concubines and attendants with proper courtesy. She bore many sons and reared them in righteousness.

    Our present sovereign lord displayed wisdom and virtue, courage and brilliance. His learning advanced daily. Before reaching his twentieth year, he passed the examinations and took office. In the cyclical year of false King Sinwu, Minister Ch'oe Yong plotted to attack the Middle Kingdom. Our High Lord, whose authority and reputation had long been established, was entrusted with command. Upholding righteousness, he withdrew his forces, seized Ch'oe Yong, and replaced him with the learned minister Yi Saek. Thus the realm found stability and our nation gained eternal benefit.

    Yi Saek urged the High Lord: "In this time of turmoil following the disturbance of the Middle Kingdom, unless the one in power personally goes to present himself at the imperial court, your loyalty cannot be vindicated before all under heaven." The High Lord replied: "If you and I both depart as ambassadors, who will govern our realm? Rather, I shall send one of my worthy sons to accompany you, which is as if I myself went." He thus dispatched our present lord as a scribe-official, and he received special honor from the High Emperor and returned.

    In autumn of that year, the Emperor issued an edict questioning the succession through another surname to the Wang line. The High Lord consulted with his generals and ministers, and they established Chongchang, a descendant of the Wang, as king.

    Before this time, treacherous officials had manipulated state affairs with impunity. When the High Lord served as prime minister, he abolished private landholdings, restored fallen laws, eliminated corruption, and brought forth proper governance—all institutions renewed. Yet high merit brings no reward, and great virtue invites jealousy. Slander and calumny were whispered ceaselessly. King Chongchang, weak and confused, could not discern right from wrong but wavered constantly. The Queen, increasingly troubled and anxious, fell ill. In autumn of the year Shinmi, on the twelfth day of the ninth month, she passed away at the age of fifty-five. With proper rites she was buried in the ancient burial ground of Sokch'on in Haepung County south of the capital.

    Our lord wished to observe the full three-year mourning period in a hut at her tomb. But in spring of the following year, the High Lord traveled westward and fell ill upon returning. Our lord came to attend his medicines, yet treacherous schemers seized this moment to intensify their plots against him. Our lord, perceiving the danger clearly, resolved to act. He struck down the ringleaders; the treacherous faction scattered like roof tiles. Chongchang, ever more fearful, was set aside.

    On the sixteenth day of the seventh month, our lord and two or three great ministers openly proclaimed the righteous cause. Without prior consultation, the officials and elders spoke with one voice, unanimously supporting the succession. The High Lord, yielding to the general sentiment, ascended the throne. Markets needed not change their operations; in a single morning the realm was cleared and brightened. A messenger was immediately sent to inform the imperial court and received successive edicts of approval. The Emperor granted royal rank and renamed the nation Joseon, restoring its fair name.

    Three years later, in the year Kapsuil, the Emperor sent an envoy commanding the ruler to present his eldest son to court. The High Lord, recognizing our lord as the most learned of his sons and most accomplished in propriety, commanded him to accompany the envoy. Upon arrival, the Emperor conversed with him, was pleased, bestowed generous rewards, and sent him home.

    In autumn of the year Muinbokk, the High Lord fell gravely ill. The treacherous official Chong Do-jeon and his faction schemed to seize power, plotting to eliminate the legitimate sons and install a lesser heir. Their conspiracy ripened toward rebellion. But our lord, perceiving their intentions with clarity, acted before they could strike. He destroyed their plots and extinguished their flames. He brought the High Lord to install the legitimate eldest as crown prince, restoring proper sequence and stabilizing the realm and its altars.

    In the ninth month, on the day Chongchuk, as the High Lord's illness would not abate, he transferred power to the crown prince. In the first month of the year Kyongchin, the rebel Park Po plotted with accomplices and incited the Prince of Hoeian to raise troops against the palace. The rebel force was formidable, yet our lord rallied the generals and soldiers and swiftly crushed the rebellion. Park Po alone was executed; the rest were pardoned. The Prince of Hoeian was spared from execution, kinship preserved.

    Since the king had no heir and our lord had accomplished both the founding and stabilization of the realm, he was made crown prince to secure the succession. On the day Kibsa of the seventh month, the jade seals and golden stamps were presented to the High Lord with the titles "Awakener of Destiny and Divine Warrior." In the eleventh month on the day Kyeyu, the king too, afflicted by illness, transferred his throne to our lord and sent envoys to petition the imperial court.

    The following year, in the year Sinsa, the Jianwen Emperor sent the official Chang Kin and the scholar Tanmu with imperial edicts and seals, formally investing our lord as king. In winter, an imperial emissary brought the formal robes and cap, conferring rank equal to a prince of the empire.

    When the present Emperor ascended the throne, our lord at once commanded his prime minister Ho Ryun to enter and present felicitations. The Emperor praised our lord's loyalty and devotion to the imperial order, granted new edicts and seals, and sent emissaries High De and Cho Ku-im in the fourth month to renew the investiture. In the ninth month, imperial envoys again arrived with the nine-patterned robe, magnificent silks and papers, gifts for the queen consort, and gifts for the High Lord—a display of favor rarely granted in the world, coming in succession.

    Indeed, the magnificent virtue and accomplishments of our lord flow from Heaven's decree, uniquely granted to this eastern realm to extend great fortune and auspicious destiny. Thus does he deserve the Emperor's profound regard and Heaven's eternal blessings.

    Though the foundation was laid by our ancestors, the blessing of bearing a sage and worthy sovereign truly derives from the Divine and Virtuous Queen.

    The Queen bore six sons. The present king is the fifth; his elder brother is the second. The eldest, Pang-u, was enfeoffed as Lord of Chinan but died young. The third, Pang-ui, was enfeoffed as Grand Lord of Iksan. The fourth, Pang-kan, was enfeoffed as Grand Lord of Hoeian. The sixth, Pang-yeon, passed the examinations but died young. Two daughters: the elder, Princess Kyongsin, married the Minister Counselor Yi Cheo; the younger, Princess Kyongseon, married the Prince of Ch'ingwon, Shim Chong.

    The present king took as his consort the Silent Consort, daughter of Min Je, Lord of Yoheung and Director of the Hall of Worthies. Their eldest son is the Crown Prince Che; younger sons are still young. The eldest daughter, Princess Chungsun, married Prince Yi Paek-kang of Ch'ingp'yong; the next, Princess Kyongcheng, married Prince Cho Dae-rim of P'yongnyong; others are still young.

    This humble minister, having observed the virtue of the great queens of ancient times, finds none surpassing the ladies of Tu-shan and the Grand Matriarch, whose names shine eternal in the records of history. The virtue of the Divine and Virtuous Queen surely bears comparison with theirs. Yet this minister's learning is shallow and his brush unskilled. Though I strive to depict such virtue, it is like attempting to paint heaven and earth—how can I capture even one ten-thousandth of her excellence?

    I dare follow the example of the Great Odes in the Classic of Poetry, particularly the "Great Brightness" and "Think of Your Virtue," and humbly compose this inscription:

    *The Sovereign High shines forth,
    Guiding and aiding the virtuous—
    Not for private favor,
    But as the ultimate service to all people.

    What was this guidance?
    The birth of graceful virtue,
    Coming to consort with excellence,
    True and fitting for the royal household.

    She bore fruit and nurtured life,
    Her spirit radiant and clear,
    Giving birth to the sage and wise,
    When heaven and earth had waited.

    Supporting the sacred father,
    She gave rise to the people's lord,
    Personally attending the imperial court,
    Preserving the security of our realm.

    When shoots of rebellion stirred,
    Her keen discernment pierced the darkness,
    Sweeping away the treachery,
    Altar and soil found their rest.

    Accomplishing his work, he yielded to another,
    Honoring the legitimate line—
    The ways of humanity restored,
    The nation's foundation strengthened.

    Faced with brothers' strife,
    He could not bear to punish,
    Preserving their lives,
    Making affection ever deeper.

    Virtue reaches toward the high,
    Accomplishment soars to the great—
    Rightly does the Supreme Lord's favor descend
    And mandate come abundantly.

    Bright, bright shines the Emperor's edict,
    Gleaming, gleaming the golden seal—
    Our sovereign lord receives them,
    Preserved for ten thousand ages.

    The king's work, traced to ancestors,
    Yet our sage and worthy lord's birth
    Flowed from the Queen's virtue alone.

    This minister bows and genuflects,
    Offering words without pretense,
    That ten thousand generations hence
    Shall know, as heaven and earth endure.*
